; corner-cases.test
;
; A grab-bag of master-file features that real zones use
; but that beginner tutorials skip:
;
;   - $ORIGIN inside the file (changes the suffix used
;     for relative names from this point on)
;   - multi-string TXT (each <character-string> is
;     length-prefixed in RDATA; a single TXT record can
;     hold any number of them, and clients reassemble
;     them in order)
;   - long TXT close to the 255-byte single-string limit
;   - deep subdomain chains (DNS labels are limited to
;     63 octets each but a name can be up to 253 octets
;     total across all labels)
;   - owner-name reuse: a leading-whitespace line means
;     "use the same owner as the previous record"
;     (the parser supports this via an internal sentinel)
;
; Try in the demo: query split.corner-cases.test for TXT
; and inspect the bytes -- you will see two length-
; prefixed strings concatenated, not one long one.
;
$ORIGIN corner-cases.test.
$TTL 3600
@               IN  SOA   ns.corner-cases.test. admin.corner-cases.test. (
                          2026010101 3600 1800 604800 86400 )
@               IN  NS    ns.corner-cases.test.
ns              IN  A     192.0.2.250
@               IN  A     192.0.2.250
@               IN  TXT   "single short string"
big             IN  TXT   "this single TXT record string is intentionally close to but not over the 255 byte single-string limit imposed by RFC 1035 and is meant to show what happens when you push that boundary"
split           IN  TXT   "first chunk of a multi-string TXT" "second chunk of the same record"
                IN  TXT   "yet another TXT at the same owner (owner reuse via leading whitespace)"
deep.deeper.deepest IN A 192.0.2.251
nested.deeply.so.much.under.corner-cases.test. IN A 192.0.2.252
$ORIGIN sub.corner-cases.test.
www             IN  A     192.0.2.230
api             IN  A     192.0.2.231
